<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings Reference
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Comprehensive reference for Event Point trigger types, listening modes, trigger fields, and practical mission authoring patterns with retail examples.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Understanding Triggers
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        An Event Point describes <Bold>what</Bold> happens — an NPC spawns, a message appears, the mission
        ends. Its trigger decides <Bold>when</Bold> that Event Point becomes active. A Create NPC with
        <Bold>None</Bold> exists from mission start. A Message with <Bold>Radius</Bold> appears when the
        player enters an area. An End Game Win with <Bold>Counter</Bold> fires when the required counter
        reaches its target.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Most retail missions use a small number of trigger patterns repeatedly: <Bold>None</Bold> for
        setup (61% of all Event Points), <Bold>Dependency</Bold> for mission chains (17%), <Bold>Radius</Bold>
        or <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> for location checks, <Bold>Counter</Bold> for objective totals, and person/object
        state triggers for mission outcomes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Rule of thumb:</Run>
                <Run> Choose the trigger based on the condition, not the Event Point type. The same Message Event Point can be radius-driven, dependency-driven, counter-driven, or person-state-driven depending on the mission moment.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings consist of several fields that work together to define when an Event Point fires:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Triggered By</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Selects the condition type that activates the Event Point. This is the main trigger selector and
        determines which other fields are relevant. For example, <Bold>Dependency</Bold> uses EP Ref,
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> uses the Radius field, and <Bold>Counter</Bold> uses both EP Ref (counter index)
        and Radius (threshold value).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Listening Mode</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Controls whether the Event Point stays active, is active only while the condition is true, runs
        for a timer, or dies after firing. The four modes are <Bold>Active</Bold> (stays active),
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> (active only while trigger is true), <Bold>Active Time</Bold> (active
        for After Timer duration), and <Bold>Active Die</Bold> (fires once then dies).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">EP Ref</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The primary Event Point reference. It commonly points at a dependency Event Point, person/NPC,
        item, vehicle, conversation, or counter index. The meaning depends on the trigger type. For
        <Bold>Dependency</Bold>, it's the Event Point being depended on. For <Bold>Killed</Bold>, it's
        the person/NPC. For <Bold>Counter</Bold>, it's the counter index (1-10).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">EP Ref Bool</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A secondary Event Point reference used by Boolean triggers, Person Seen, Person In Vehicle, and
        similar two-reference triggers. For <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold> and <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold>, EP Ref
        is the first Event Point and EP Ref Bool is the second. For <Bold>Person Seen</Bold>, EP Ref is
        the person being seen and EP Ref Bool is the observer.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Radius</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A multipurpose field whose meaning depends on the trigger type. For <Bold>Radius</Bold> triggers,
        it stores distance. For <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> triggers, it stores packed cuboid dimensions (low half
        = X half-size, high half = Z half-size). For <Bold>Counter</Bold> triggers, it stores the threshold
        value. For <Bold>Countdown</Bold> and <Bold>Visible Countdown</Bold>, it stores the timer duration
        in engine ticks or mission time units. For <Bold>Crime Rate</Bold> triggers, it stores the threshold
        as percent × 100 (9900 = 99%). Always check the trigger type to interpret this field correctly.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">After Timer</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Used by <Bold>Active Time</Bold> listening mode to control how long the Event Point stays active
        after firing. The value is in mission time units or engine ticks depending on context. This field
        is ignored by other listening modes.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Invert Condition</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Negates the trigger condition where the engine supports it. For example, <Bold>Radius</Bold> with
        Invert would fire when the player is <Bold>outside</Bold> the radius instead of inside. Not all
        trigger types support inversion. Test carefully before relying on inverted triggers.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ========================================
         LISTENING MODES SECTION
         ======================================== -->

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Listening Modes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,0,0,12">
        Listening modes control how an Event Point behaves after its trigger condition is met. They determine
        whether the Event Point stays active permanently, only while the trigger is true, for a limited time,
        or fires once and dies.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ACTIVE -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Active</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Event Point becomes active once the trigger condition is met and remains active as a valid
        dependency target for later mission logic. This is the safest default for most authored mission
        chains and the most common listening mode in retail missions.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Active
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active</Bold> when the Event Point should fire once and then remain available for other
        Event Points to depend on. This is appropriate for most mission objectives, checkpoints, and
        scripted events that mark permanent progress. Once active, the Event Point stays active for the
        rest of the mission unless explicitly killed by other logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. It remains
        active even if the trigger condition later becomes false. For example, a <Bold>Radius</Bold>
        trigger with <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode fires when the player enters the radius and stays
        active even after the player leaves.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Dependency chains:</Bold> A Conversation Event Point with <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger
        and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode starts when the player talks to an NPC. It stays active,
        allowing later Event Points to use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> or <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on it.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Checkpoint triggers:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and
        <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode shows an objective message when the player enters an area.
        The message remains visible (and the Event Point remains active) even after the player leaves,
        marking the checkpoint as reached.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>State changes:</Bold> A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger and
        <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode spawns enemy reinforcements when a previous objective completes.
        The group stays alive (and the Event Point stays active) for the rest of the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Active is the safest default for most Event Points. Use it unless you specifically need Active While (continuous state), Active Time (timed effect), or Active Die (one-shot cleanup).</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ACTIVE WHILE -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Active While</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Event Point is active only while the trigger condition remains true. When the condition becomes
        false, the Event Point becomes inactive. This is used for continuous states like being inside an
        area, holding an item, or being in a vehicle where later logic should stop being true when the
        condition stops.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Active While
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> when the Event Point should be active only as long as the trigger
        condition is true. This is appropriate for temporary states, area-based effects, and conditional
        logic that should deactivate when the player leaves or the condition changes. If another Event
        Point depends on an Active While Event Point, that dependency is only valid while the condition
        remains true.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. When the
        condition becomes false, the Event Point becomes inactive. This can happen repeatedly — the Event
        Point toggles between active and inactive based on the trigger condition. For example, a
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger with <Bold>Active While</Bold> is active while the player is inside
        the radius and inactive when outside.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Area messages:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> or <Bold>Cuboid</Bold>
        trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold> listening mode shows a message while the player is inside
        the area. When the player leaves, the Event Point becomes inactive and the message disappears.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Continuous effects:</Bold> A Shake Camera Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger
        and <Bold>Active While</Bold> listening mode shakes the camera continuously while a boss attack
        or machine is active. When the triggering Event Point becomes inactive, the shake stops.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Conditional dependencies:</Bold> An enemy spawn Event Point with <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold>
        trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold> would spawn enemies only while the player holds the item.
        When the player drops the item, the Event Point becomes inactive and the enemies despawn (if the
        Event Point type supports despawning).
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Active While can break dependency chains if the source Event Point becomes inactive before dependent Event Points fire. Test carefully when using Active While as a dependency source.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ACTIVE TIME -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Active Time</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Event Point becomes active for a limited period controlled by the <Bold>After Timer</Bold>
        field. After the timer expires, the Event Point becomes inactive. This is used for temporary
        effects, timed windows, or logic that should pulse for a short duration.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Active Time
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active Time</Bold> when an effect should last for a specific duration rather than
        staying active permanently or toggling with a condition. This is appropriate for temporary audio
        effects, timed powerups, brief messages, or scripted events that should automatically end after
        a set time.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. It stays active
        for the duration specified in <Bold>After Timer</Bold> (in mission time units or engine ticks),
        then becomes inactive. The Event Point does not reactivate unless the trigger fires again.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Temporary sounds:</Bold> A sound effect Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger
        and <Bold>Active Time</Bold> listening mode plays a sound for the specified duration when triggered,
        then stops automatically.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Timed buffs:</Bold> A powerup or buff Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> grants a temporary effect when the player enters an area, lasting for
        the After Timer duration.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Brief messages:</Bold> A hint or warning Message Event Point with <Bold>Active Time</Bold>
        shows a message for a few seconds then disappears, without requiring manual dismissal.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Active Time is less common than Active, Active While, or Active Die. Test the After Timer value to ensure the duration is appropriate for the effect.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ACTIVE DIE -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Active Die</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Event Point fires once when the trigger condition is met, then becomes inactive/dead. The
        Event Point will not fire again and is no longer available as a dependency target. This is used
        for one-shot actions like sounds, camera shakes, group state changes, or scripted events that
        should not repeatedly retrigger.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Active Die
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active Die</Bold> when an Event Point should fire exactly once and then stop processing.
        This is appropriate for mission-start setup logic (Group Death, Group Life), one-time scripted
        events, cleanup actions, and effects that should never repeat. After firing, the Event Point
        becomes dead and cannot be depended on by later logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires once and immediately becomes
        inactive/dead. It will not fire again even if the trigger condition becomes true again. If another
        Event Point has a <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on an Active Die Event Point, that dependency must fire
        immediately when the Active Die Event Point fires, or it will miss the window and never fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Mission-start setup:</Bold> A Group Death Event Point with <Bold>None</Bold> trigger and
        <Bold>Active Die</Bold> listening mode kills a group at mission start, then the Event Point itself
        becomes inactive. This prevents the Event Point from continuing to process after its job is done.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>One-shot sounds:</Bold> A sound effect Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger
        and <Bold>Active Die</Bold> plays a sound once when triggered, then dies, preventing the sound
        from repeating if the trigger somehow fires again.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Scripted cleanup:</Bold> An Event Point that performs a one-time cleanup action (removing
        objects, killing groups, resetting state) uses <Bold>Active Die</Bold> to ensure it only happens
        once.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Active Die Event Points cannot be reliable dependency sources because they become inactive immediately after firing. If another Event Point depends on an Active Die Event Point, it must fire in the same frame or it will miss the dependency.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ========================================
         TRIGGER TYPES SECTION
         ======================================== -->

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,0,0,12">
        Trigger types define the condition that causes an Event Point to fire. The most common types are
        None (mission start), Dependency (chained objectives), spatial triggers (Radius, Cuboid), and
        state-based triggers (Killed, Person Used, Conversation Over).
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- NONE -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">None</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Event Point is active immediately when the mission loads. No trigger condition is required.
        This is the most common trigger type in retail missions, accounting for <Bold>61% of all Event
        Points</Bold> (9,983 of 16,259).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use None
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>None</Bold> for player spawn points, default NPCs, placed items, ambient effects,
        always-available vehicles, and setup logic that should exist from the beginning of the mission.
        This is the default trigger for any Event Point that should be active at mission start without
        waiting for a condition.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        No trigger reference fields are used. <Bold>EP Ref</Bold>, <Bold>EP Ref Bool</Bold>, and
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> are ignored. Only the listening mode matters.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Player spawn:</Bold> The player spawn point (Activate Event Point) always uses <Bold>None</Bold>
        trigger with <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode. This is present in every retail mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Ambient NPCs:</Bold> Create NPC Event Points for ambient civilians, background characters,
        and default enemies use <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> to spawn at mission start.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Mission-start group state:</Bold> Group Death and Group Life Event Points that set initial
        group states use <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active Die</Bold> or <Bold>Active</Bold> to configure
        groups at mission start.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In nearly every retail mission, the player spawn point uses <Bold>None</Bold> trigger. Most ambient
        NPCs, placed vehicles, and default mission setup Event Points use <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold>.
        Group Death Event Points that keep enemy groups dormant at mission start use <Bold>None</Bold>
        with <Bold>Active Die</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Use Active for normal persistent setup. Use Active Die only if the Event Point performs a one-time action and should not remain available as a dependency.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- DEPENDENCY -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Dependency</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Waits for another Event Point to become active or complete. This is the second most common trigger
        type in retail missions (<Bold>17% of all Event Points</Bold>, 2,787 instances) and is the standard
        way to chain objectives and create mission flow.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Dependency
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> whenever one Event Point should fire after another completes. This is
        appropriate for objective chains (show message 2 after message 1 completes), scripted sequences
        (spawn enemy wave 2 after wave 1 is defeated), and conditional logic (open door after player
        collects key). Most mission objectives are chained together using <Bold>Dependency</Bold> triggers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> is the Event Point index being depended on. When that Event Point becomes
        active, this Event Point fires. The listening mode of the source Event Point matters:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the source uses <Bold>Active</Bold>, it stays active after firing, making it a reliable dependency target.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the source uses <Bold>Active Die</Bold>, it becomes inactive immediately after firing. Dependencies must fire in the same frame or they will miss.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the source uses <Bold>Active While</Bold>, the dependency is only valid while the source condition remains true. The dependent Event Point will deactivate when the source deactivates.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Objective chain:</Bold> Message Event Point 2 depends on Message Event Point 1. When the
        player completes objective 1 (triggering Message 1), Message 2 fires to show the next objective.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Wave spawn:</Bold> A Group Life Event Point depends on a Group Dead or Killed Event Point.
        When the previous enemy wave is defeated, the next wave spawns.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Post-conversation logic:</Bold> An Event Point depends on a Conversation Event Point. When
        the conversation finishes, the dependent Event Point fires (usually combined with Conversation
        Over trigger for more precise timing).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In nearly every retail mission, Message and Nav Beacon Event Points use <Bold>Dependency</Bold>
        to chain objectives. For example, an objective completion Message depends on the Event Point that
        represents completing that objective (killing a target, reaching an area, collecting an item).
        Group Life Event Points often use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> to spawn enemy waves after previous
        waves are defeated.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> If a Dependency appears unreliable, check the source Event Point's listening mode. Active While sources become inactive when their condition stops, which can break dependencies. Active Die sources fire once and die, which works for most dependency chains but can miss if timing is off.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- RADIUS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Radius</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether the player (or relevant actor) is within a circular area around the Event Point's
        position. This is a spatial trigger used for area entry, objective proximity, local warnings, and
        trigger volumes. Retail missions use <Bold>Radius</Bold> 146 times across 76 missions.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Radius
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Radius</Bold> for area-based objectives, proximity triggers, location checks, and
        circular trigger volumes. This is appropriate when the player must enter a specific location or
        get close to an objective. Use <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> instead when a rectangular area is needed
        (rooms, alleys, building interiors).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> stores the distance threshold in map units. <Bold>Position</Bold> and
        <Bold>Y altitude</Bold> matter because the check is spatial — the Event Point's position is the
        center of the circular trigger area. The player must be within the specified distance from the
        Event Point's position for the trigger to fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Area entry checkpoint:</Bold> A Message or Nav Beacon Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold>
        trigger and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode fires when the player enters the area and stays
        active (marking the checkpoint as reached).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Temporary area message:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> listening mode shows a message while the player is inside the area.
        When the player leaves, the message disappears.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Proximity objective:</Bold> An objective Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger fires
        when the player approaches a target location, NPC, or object.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Radius triggers are commonly used for Nav Beacon Event Points that should appear when the player
        approaches an objective location, and for Message Event Points that show area-specific text.
        Many stealth missions use <Bold>Radius</Bold> triggers to detect when the player enters restricted
        areas or approaches guards.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Position the Event Point at the center of the desired trigger area and set Radius to the distance from center to edge. For rectangular areas, use Cuboid instead.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- CUBOID -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Cuboid</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether the player or target is inside a rectangular box (cuboid). This is more precise
        than <Bold>Radius</Bold> for rooms, alleys, building entrances, and rectangular zones where a
        circular radius would spill into the wrong space. Retail missions use <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> 330
        times, making it one of the most common spatial triggers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Cuboid
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> for building interiors, rectangular rooms, alleys, corridors, and any
        area where <Bold>Radius</Bold> would create a circular area that extends into unwanted space.
        <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> allows precise control over rectangular trigger volumes that align with
        building walls and street layouts.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> stores packed dimensions: the low 16 bits are the X half-size, and the high
        16 bits are the Z half-size. The Event Point's <Bold>Position</Bold> is the center of the cuboid.
        For example, if Radius = 1310720 (0x00140000), the low half is 0 and the high half is 20, meaning
        X half-size = 0 and Z half-size = 20. The actual cuboid extends from the center position by these
        half-sizes in each direction.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Building entry:</Bold> A Cuboid trigger detects when the player enters a specific building.
        The Event Point is placed at the building's center with dimensions matching the building's
        rectangular footprint.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Room-specific objectives:</Bold> A Message or objective Event Point with <Bold>Cuboid</Bold>
        trigger fires when the player enters a specific room within a larger building.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Alley chase sequences:</Bold> A Cuboid trigger follows the player through narrow alleys
        where a circular Radius would trigger outside the alley boundaries.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Many retail missions use <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> triggers for building entry detection, room-specific
        objectives, and alley chase sequences. For example, a mission objective that requires the player
        to enter a specific building uses a <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> trigger placed at the building's center
        with dimensions matching the building's rectangular footprint.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- PERSON USED -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Person Used</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether the player has used or interacted with a person/NPC. This is the third most common
        trigger type (<Bold>640 instances</Bold>) and is primarily used to start conversations, trigger
        interrogations, initiate rescue interactions, and create talk-to-character objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Person Used
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Person Used</Bold> for conversation starts, interrogations, rescue interactions, and
        talk-to-NPC objectives. This is the standard trigger for any Event Point that should fire when
        the player interacts with a specific NPC.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The relevant person is usually implied by the Event Point's position or mission context. Some
        implementations may use <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to identify the specific NPC, but in most retail
        examples, the trigger fires when the player interacts with any NPC near the Event Point's location.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Conversation start:</Bold> A Conversation Event Point with <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger
        and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode starts when the player talks to an NPC. The Event Point
        stays active, allowing later logic to use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> to chain follow-up actions.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Interrogation:</Bold> An interrogation Event Point with <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger
        starts when the player interacts with a suspect or witness NPC.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Rescue interaction:</Bold> A rescue objective Event Point with <Bold>Person Used</Bold>
        trigger completes when the player interacts with a hostage or civilian NPC.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Nearly all Conversation Event Points in retail missions use <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger.
        For example, a mission objective to talk to a witness uses a Conversation Event Point with
        <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger placed at the witness's location. When the player interacts
        with the witness, the conversation starts.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- KILLED -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Killed</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether a referenced person/NPC has been killed. This is used for lethal objectives,
        enemy elimination logic, and assassination missions. <Bold>430 instances</Bold> in retail missions.
        Do not use <Bold>Killed</Bold> when arresting should also count as success — use <Bold>Person
        Arrested</Bold> or <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> to combine both conditions.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Killed
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Killed</Bold> for assassination targets, enemy bosses, and lethal objectives where the
        player must eliminate a specific NPC. This is appropriate when only killing (not arresting) should
        satisfy the objective. Pair with Message or Nav Beacon Event Points that depend on the Killed
        trigger to show objective completion feedback.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> points at the person/NPC Event Point (usually a Create NPC or Create Creature).
        When that NPC's health reaches zero and they die, this Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Boss defeat:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Killed</Bold> trigger on the boss NPC
        shows the victory message when the boss dies.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Wave completion:</Bold> A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Killed</Bold> trigger on the
        last enemy in a wave spawns the next wave when that enemy dies.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Assassination objective:</Bold> An objective Event Point with <Bold>Killed</Bold> trigger
        on the target NPC completes when the target is eliminated.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Many combat missions use <Bold>Killed</Bold> triggers to detect when key enemy NPCs are eliminated.
        For example, a boss battle objective uses a <Bold>Killed</Bold> trigger on the boss NPC, then a
        Message Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on that Killed trigger shows the victory message.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- CONVERSATION OVER -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Conversation Over</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether a Conversation Event Point has finished. This is used to chain logic after dialogue
        and is usually more accurate than depending on the conversation start. <Bold>361 instances</Bold>
        in retail missions make this one of the most common conversation-related triggers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Conversation Over
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> to chain objective updates, spawn enemy waves, unlock doors,
        or trigger scripted events after a conversation finishes. This ensures the player has seen all
        the dialogue before the next mission beat occurs.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> points at the Conversation Event Point. When that conversation finishes
        (all dialogue lines complete), this Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Post-dialogue spawn:</Bold> A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold>
        trigger spawns enemies after an informant conversation warns the player about them.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Post-dialogue unlock:</Bold> A door unlock or area access Event Point with <Bold>Conversation
        Over</Bold> trigger grants access after an NPC tells the player where to go.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Objective update:</Bold> A Message or Nav Beacon Event Point with <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold>
        trigger shows the next objective after the player finishes talking to an NPC.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Story-heavy missions use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> extensively. For example, after an
        informant conversation, a <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> trigger spawns the enemies the informant
        warned about, or unlocks the door the informant mentioned.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- BOOLEAN AND -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Boolean AND</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Combines two trigger conditions and succeeds only when both are true. This is used for objectives
        with two prerequisites, such as collecting an item AND talking to a person. <Bold>359 instances</Bold>
        in retail missions make this the most common Boolean operator.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Boolean AND
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold> for objectives requiring multiple completion conditions. This creates
        branching objectives where the player can complete prerequisites in any order, but must complete
        all of them before the combined objective succeeds.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> is the first Event Point. <Bold>EP Ref Bool</Bold> is the second Event Point.
        Both must be active for this Event Point to fire. The order usually does not matter — either can
        complete first and the trigger will fire when both are true.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Multi-step objective:</Bold> Collect evidence AND escort witness to safety. A <Bold>Boolean
        AND</Bold> Event Point references both the evidence-collected Event Point and the witness-safe
        Event Point.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Dual requirements:</Bold> Kill target A AND destroy object B. The objective completes only
        when both conditions are met.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Area and item:</Bold> Reach area A AND hold item B. Useful for objectives that require the
        player to bring something to a specific location.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Missions with multi-step objectives use <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold>. For example, a mission objective
        requires collecting evidence AND escorting a witness to safety. A <Bold>Boolean AND</Bold> Event
        Point references both prerequisite Event Points, firing only when both conditions are met.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- BOOLEAN OR -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Boolean OR</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Combines two trigger conditions and succeeds when either is true. This is used for alternate
        routes or objectives where multiple solutions are valid. <Bold>121 instances</Bold> in retail
        missions.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Boolean OR
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> for objectives with alternate solutions. This gives players choice
        and flexibility, allowing multiple paths to the same goal.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> is the first Event Point. <Bold>EP Ref Bool</Bold> is the second Event Point.
        If either becomes active, this Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Alternate routes:</Bold> Reach area A OR reach area B (two different paths to the same
        objective).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Lethal or non-lethal:</Bold> Kill target A OR arrest target A. The objective completes
        either way.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Multiple informants:</Bold> Talk to witness A OR talk to witness B. Either conversation
        provides the needed information.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Missions with branching paths use <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold>. For example, an objective can be
        completed by either sneaking through area A or fighting through area B. A <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold>
        Event Point references both path-complete Event Points, firing when either route is taken.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- COUNTER -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Counter</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Checks whether a mission counter has reached a required value. This is used with Increment Event
        Points for count-based objectives like kill counts, collection counts, and multi-step totals.
        Retail missions use Counter triggers in combination with Increment Event Points (46 instances of
        Increment across retail missions).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Counter
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Counter</Bold> for objectives like "kill 10 enemies" or "collect 5 items." Create
        Increment Event Points that add to the counter when enemies die or items are collected, then use
        a <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger to fire an objective-complete Event Point when the count reaches
        the target.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> stores the counter index (1-10). <Bold>Radius</Bold> stores the required
        threshold value. When the counter (incremented by Increment Event Points) reaches or exceeds the
        threshold, this Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Kill count objective:</Bold> Increment Event Points on each enemy NPC (triggered by Killed)
        increment counter 1. A Message Event Point with <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger (counter 1, threshold
        10) shows success when 10 enemies are eliminated.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Collection objective:</Bold> Increment Event Points on item pickups increment counter 2.
        A Counter trigger fires when all items are collected.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Multi-phase counter:</Bold> Increment adds to a counter during phase 1. Counter trigger
        checks threshold and completes phase 1. Reset Counter clears the count for phase 2 reuse.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Missions with kill-count objectives use <Bold>Counter</Bold> triggers. For example, an objective
        to eliminate 8 gang members uses Increment Event Points on each gang member NPC (triggered by
        Killed), all incrementing counter 1. A Message Event Point with <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger
        (counter 1, threshold 8) shows the success message when all 8 are eliminated.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- Continue with other common triggers... -->
    <!-- For brevity, I'll add a few more key ones and then the "Less Common Triggers" summary section -->

    <!-- COUNTDOWN -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Countdown</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Runs or checks a hidden countdown timer. This is used for timed logic that does not need to be
        shown to the player. <Bold>157 instances</Bold> in retail missions. Use <Bold>Visible Countdown</Bold>
        instead when the timer should be displayed to the player.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Countdown
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Countdown</Bold> for delayed scripted events, timed delays between mission beats, or
        hidden timers that control mission pacing without showing the player a countdown clock.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> stores the timer/countdown amount in engine ticks or mission time units.
        When the Event Point becomes active, the timer starts counting down. When it reaches zero, the
        Event Point fires (or becomes inactive, depending on listening mode).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Delayed spawn:</Bold> A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Countdown</Bold> trigger waits
        a certain duration after mission start before spawning reinforcements.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Alarm delay:</Bold> After an alarm triggers, a <Bold>Countdown</Bold> Event Point waits
        before spawning police, giving the player a brief window to escape.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Many missions use <Bold>Countdown</Bold> for timed delays. For example, after an alarm triggers,
        a <Bold>Countdown</Bold> Event Point waits a certain duration before spawning reinforcement NPCs,
        giving the player a brief window to react.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- VISIBLE COUNTDOWN -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Visible Countdown</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Runs a countdown visible to the player. This is used for timed objectives where the player needs
        to see the remaining time. <Bold>25 instances</Bold> in retail missions. Pair with Extend Timer
        Event Points when time can be increased.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        When To Use Visible Countdown
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Visible Countdown</Bold> for timed objectives like defusing bombs, escaping before
        destruction, or completing tasks within a time limit. The countdown is shown to the player on
        the HUD, creating urgency and time pressure.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Radius</Bold> stores the timer value in mission time units. <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> can be
        used as a dependency or timer target in chained logic. The countdown is shown to the player on
        the HUD.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Bomb defusal:</Bold> A Visible Countdown shows the time remaining to defuse a bomb. An
        End Game Lose Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on the timer fires if time runs out.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Escape sequence:</Bold> A Visible Countdown shows time to reach the extraction point before
        the building explodes or the police arrive.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Bomb-defusal missions use <Bold>Visible Countdown</Bold> extensively. The player sees the timer
        counting down and must complete the objective before time expires. An End Game Lose Event Point
        with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on the timer fires if time runs out.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- LESS COMMON TRIGGERS SUMMARY -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Additional Trigger Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The following triggers are used less frequently but are documented for completeness. Each has
        specific use cases in retail missions:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Enemy Radius (169 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks enemy proximity. Use for ambush triggers, stealth penalties, or proximity alerts.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Person Seen (125 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks if a person has been seen by an observer. Use for stealth fail conditions and guard detection.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Player Uses Radius (124 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Requires player interaction within a radius. Use for doors, consoles, and interactive objects.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Killed Not Arrested (97 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks that a person was killed (not arrested). Use for fail conditions in non-lethal missions.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Random (92 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Allows randomized trigger outcomes. Use sparingly for non-deterministic mission behaviour.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Person Arrested (79 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks if a person was arrested. Use for police/non-lethal objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Group Dead (44 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks if all members of a Colour+Group are dead. Use for wave-clear objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Prim Damaged (30 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks if a prim/object was damaged. Use for destructible objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Specific Item Held (27 instances)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Checks if the player holds a specific item. Use for key-and-lock objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Tripwire, Switch, Pressure Pad, Half Dead, Item Held, Crime Rate Above/Below, Person In Vehicle, Thing Radius Dir, Player Fires Gun, Player Carry Person, Move Radius Dir</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Specialized triggers with fewer than 25 instances each. See individual documentation or retail
        examples for specific usage patterns.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Legacy Triggers (Door, Electric Fence, Water Level, Security Camera, Anim Prim, Darci Grabbed, Punched And Kicked, Shout All/Any, Item Seen, Person Is Murderer)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Legacy or character-specific triggers. Use modern alternatives (Activate Prim, Radius, Player Uses
        Radius) for new content unless loading existing mission data that relies on these trigger types.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Authoring Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Objective Chain Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Message or Nav Beacon uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on the Event Point that completed the previous
        step. This creates sequential objective chains where each depends on the previous one completing.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Area Objective Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Message, Conversation, or Create NPC uses <Bold>Radius</Bold> or <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> at the
        relevant map position. This creates location-based objectives where the player must reach a
        specific area.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Count Objective Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Increment updates a counter (triggered by Killed, Person Arrested, or other completion conditions),
        <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger checks the threshold and fires the objective-complete Event Point,
        and Reset Counter clears the value when the objective restarts or the mission phase changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Dialogue Chain Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Conversation starts from <Bold>Person Used</Bold> or <Bold>Radius</Bold>, then follow-up logic
        uses <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> to chain the next mission beat. This ensures the player
        completes the dialogue before the mission progresses.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Item Gate Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> points at the item Event Point, then activates vehicle, door,
        target, or message logic. This creates key-and-lock style objectives where the player must
        collect a specific item to progress.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Group Objective Pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Life, Group Death, Group Reset, and <Bold>Group Dead</Bold> trigger must use consistent
        Colour+Group values across all related Event Points. This creates wave-based enemy encounters
        and group-elimination objectives.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Debugging tip:</Run>
                <Run> If a trigger does not behave as expected, inspect the referenced Event Point first, then the listening mode, then the Radius field meaning. Many trigger problems are caused by treating Radius as a distance when the selected trigger type stores a timer, counter threshold, packed cuboid size, or crime-rate value.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

